            <biogHist>
                <p>James Andrew MacRae was born on North Uist, the son of Finlay MacRae, minister,
                    and Isabella Maria MacRae n√©e MacDonald.  In the 1841 census, he is found in
                    Vallay on North Uist age 6 together with five siblings: Donald (15), Alexander
                    (13), Duncan (10), John (8) and Jane (4). In the 1861 census, he is listed as a
                    visitor to the household of Thomas Craigie in Perth and is described as
                    'Captain, Inverness [H S I] Militia'.  In 1871, the census finds him back on
                    North Uist and now the head of the household, his mother having been widowed;
                    five servants are also listed.  At this time, he is described as 'Farmer and
                    Captain, Inverness [H I S] Militia'; by the time of his death he had become a
                    Major.</p>
                <p>James Andrew MacRae (listed as 'Major' on the death certificate) died in Vallay,
                    North Uist of pulmonary consumption at the age of 39 on 17 November 1873 and his
                    brother John A. MacRae witnessed the certificate. </p>
                <p>Alexander Carmichael collected a story about Vikings and seals from James Andrew
                    MacRae around 1875.</p>
